"""
mkt-context — 2 Samuel 4–7
run: python3 scripts/zc-context-2samuel-4-7.py

Ch4: Ish-bosheth's assassination — Beeroth geography, David's precedent re: killing YHWH's anointed
Ch5: David over all Israel — Jerusalem's conquest (Warren's Shaft), City of David archaeology,
     Hiram's cedar trade, Philistine Valley of Rephaim battles
Ch6: Ark to Jerusalem — new-cart error (Num 4:15), Uzzah, Obed-edom (Levite gatekeeper),
     Michal window motif, David's linen ephod
Ch7: Davidic covenant — ANE temple-building ideology, bayit wordplay, Nathan's oracle structure,
     David's prayer model; v1 already written by prior agent
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

SAMUEL2 = {
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>When Ish-bosheth son of Saul heard that Abner had died at Hebron, his courage failed and all Israel was dismayed. Ish-bosheth (<em>ʾîš-bōšeṯ</em>, man of shame) was likely named Esh-baal (man of Baal) at birth — 1 Chr 8:33 preserves the original form — and had the theophoric element replaced with <em>bōšeṯ</em> (shame) by later scribal convention, as happened with several Saulide names. He ruled the northern tribes from Mahanaim in Transjordan for two years (2:10), sustained politically by Abner's military support. With Abner dead (3:27), the political infrastructure of the rival kingdom has collapsed.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Saul's son had two men who were commanders of raiding bands (<em>śārê gəḏûḏîm</em>): Baanah and Rechab, sons of Rimmon the Beerothite, from the tribe of Benjamin. The <em>gəḏûḏ</em> (raiding party/band) was a tactical unit used for swift strikes — distinct from the main army. These two men hold a rank that gave them access to the royal quarters without arousing suspicion.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'The Beerothites fled to Gittaim and are sojourners there to this day.' Beeroth was one of the four Hivite-Gibeonite cities that deceived Israel into a treaty in Josh 9:17. The flight to Gittaim is unexplained in the narrative but likely reflects the aftermath of Saul's attack on the Gibeonites (referenced in 21:2) — the Beerothites, as Gibeonite confederates, fled when Saul's aggression began. Their status as <em>gērîm</em> (resident aliens) in Gittaim connects forward to the Gibeonite reparations of ch21.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A parenthetical note: Jonathan's son Mephibosheth was five years old when the news of Saul and Jonathan came from Jezreel. His nurse took him and fled; in her hurry he fell and became lame in both feet. This parenthesis prepares for David's treatment of Mephibosheth in ch9. The note is placed here — in the middle of the Ish-bosheth narrative — to remind the reader of the last surviving claimant to the Saulide throne and his disability. The information that he fell while fleeing frames his lameness as a consequence of the same crisis (Saul's death) that eliminated the rest of his family.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Baanah and Rechab set out and came to the house of Ish-bosheth at the heat of the day, while he was taking his midday rest. The 'heat of the day' is the siesta period in which the household would be less guarded — the same temporal setting as David's fateful rooftop encounter in 11:2. The narrative's detail about Ish-bosheth taking his rest emphasizes his vulnerability and the opportunistic timing of the assassination.</p>",
    "6": "<p>They came into the middle of the house as if to get wheat, and they stabbed him in the stomach. The pretext — fetching wheat from the house's store — gave them access to the interior without armed escort. The quick, decisive nature of the attack (<em>wayyakkūhû ʾel-haḥōmeš</em>, they struck him in the belly) ensured Ish-bosheth had no opportunity to resist or call for help.</p>",
    "7": "<p>They came into the house while he was lying on his bed in his bedroom and struck him and put him to death and beheaded him. They took his head and went by the way of the Arabah all night. The Arabah route — the Jordan Valley running south from the Sea of Galilee to the Dead Sea — was the direct road from Mahanaim to Hebron, bypassing the central highlands where they might be recognized. They traveled by night to avoid detection, bringing the head as physical proof of their deed for David.</p>",
    "8": "<p>They brought the head of Ish-bosheth to David at Hebron and said to the king: Here is the head of Ish-bosheth, the son of Saul, your enemy, who sought your life. YHWH has avenged my lord the king this day on Saul and his offspring. The killers frame their act as divinely executed justice — the same justification the Amalekite used in 1:10-16 when he claimed to have killed Saul. Both attempts to curry David's favor by producing the death of a Saulide backfired severely.</p>",
    "9": "<p>David answered Rechab and Baanah his brother, sons of Rimmon the Beerothite: As YHWH lives, who has redeemed my life from every adversity. David's response begins with a divine oath — <em>ḥay YHWH ʾăšer pāḏāh ʾeṯ-napšî mikol-ṣārāh</em> — and immediately establishes that YHWH, not human action, is the agent of his survival. The term <em>pāḏâ</em> (redeemed/ransomed) is the commercial-legal term for buying someone out of obligation — David's life has been protected by YHWH's own action, not by the murders these men have committed.</p>",
    "10": "<p>When one told me, Saul is dead, thinking he was bringing good news, I seized him and killed him at Ziklag — that was the reward I gave him for his news. David cites the precedent of 1:1-16: he executed the Amalekite messenger who claimed to have killed Saul. The principle is now applied retroactively to establish what these men should have expected. The word <em>bəśōrāh</em> (good news) is used ironically — what the messenger thought was news that would earn him a reward was instead the ground of his execution.</p>",
    "11": "<p>How much more, when wicked men have killed a righteous man in his own house on his own bed, shall I not now require his blood at your hand and destroy you from the earth? David's legal reasoning is explicit: if executing the messenger who reported Saul's death was just (even though Saul had been David's persecutor), executing the murderers of Ish-bosheth (<em>ṣaddîq</em>, righteous/innocent) is even more clearly required. The <em>ṣaddîq</em> designation for Ish-bosheth does not mean morally superior to David but legally innocent of any offense against David.</p>",
    "12": "<p>David commanded his young men, and they killed them and cut off their hands and their feet and hanged them beside the pool at Hebron. But they took the head of Ish-bosheth and buried it in the tomb of Abner at Hebron. The mutilation — cutting off hands and feet — is a form of public execution and display that denies the offenders a proper burial while communicating the king's condemnation. The pool at Hebron was a public location; the displayed bodies served as a warning. The burial of Ish-bosheth's head in Abner's tomb is an act of respect that reconnects the murdered son of Saul with his general — both are given honorable burial under David's authority.</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>Then all the tribes of Israel came to David at Hebron and said: We are your bone and flesh. The phrase <em>ʿaṣməḵā ûḇəśārəḵā</em> (your bone and your flesh) is the covenant kinship formula first used by Laban to Jacob (Gen 29:14) and later by Abimelech appealing to Shechem (Judg 9:2). It signifies genuine genealogical and covenant kinship — the northern tribes are asserting that the political division after Saul's death was never a repudiation of their bond with David but a temporary alignment with Ish-bosheth that has now ended.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Even when Saul was our king, it was you who led Israel out and brought it back. And YHWH said to you: You shall shepherd (<em>tirʿeh</em>) my people Israel, and you shall be prince (<em>nāgîd</em>) over Israel. The dual vocabulary — <em>rōʿeh</em> (shepherd) and <em>nāgîd</em> (designated leader, not the more dynastic <em>melek</em>) — is significant. The shepherd image comes from David's background (1 Sam 16-17) and from ANE royal ideology where the king is the shepherd of his people (Hammurabi's code prologue, Assyrian royal inscriptions). <em>nāgîd</em> (rather than <em>melek</em>) emphasizes the appointment comes from YHWH, not from popular acclamation or dynastic succession.</p>",
    "3": "<p>So all the elders of Israel came to King David at Hebron, and King David made a covenant with them at Hebron before YHWH, and they anointed David king over Israel. David's third anointing: first by Samuel (1 Sam 16:13), second by the men of Judah at Hebron (2:4), now by all Israel at Hebron. Each anointing marks a stage of the Davidic kingship's expansion. The covenant David makes with the elders (<em>wayyikrōṯ lāhem dāwid bərîṯ</em>) is the formal political compact of the constitutional monarchy — the king has obligations to the people as well as authority over them.</p>",
    "4": "<p>David was thirty years old when he became king (<em>ben-šəlōšîm šānāh dāwid bəmālkô</em>), and he reigned forty years. The note of age and total reign is the regnal formula used throughout Kings — standardized biographical data for each monarch. David's age thirty is significant: the same age at which Levites began their tabernacle service (Num 4:3) and at which Joseph entered Pharaoh's service (Gen 41:46). Later tradition noted that Jesus began his ministry at about thirty (Luke 3:23), likely in conscious resonance with these precedents.</p>",
    "5": "<p>At Hebron he reigned over Judah seven years and six months, and at Jerusalem he reigned over all Israel and Judah thirty-three years. The two-capital structure — seven-and-a-half years at Hebron over Judah, then thirty-three years at Jerusalem over all Israel — frames the total of forty years. Jerusalem becomes the capital that unifies the northern and southern tribal blocks precisely because it was not previously associated with either grouping.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The king and his men went to Jerusalem against the Jebusites, the inhabitants of the land, who said to David: You will not come in here, but the blind and lame will turn you back — thinking: David cannot come in here. Jerusalem had remained unconquered through the entire period of the judges (Judg 1:21: the tribe of Benjamin did not drive out the Jebusites). The Jebusite taunt about 'the blind and the lame' defending the city is interpreted in v8 — it may reference the Jebusite belief that their disabled would be sufficient to defend them, or possibly that images/statues were placed on the walls. The strategic value of Jerusalem as a neutral site on the tribal border of Benjamin and Judah was exactly why David chose it.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Nevertheless, David took the stronghold of Zion — that is, the City of David. Zion (<em>ṣiyyôn</em>) appears here for the first time as the name for the Jebusite stronghold. Its etymology is uncertain; it becomes the primary theological name for Jerusalem in the Psalms and prophets. The 'City of David' designation begins here — the southeastern ridge of the Ophel, the oldest part of the city, which has been the focus of archaeological excavations from Kathleen Kenyon (1961-67) through Eilat Mazar and Yosef Garfinkel in more recent decades.</p>",
    "8": "<p>David said on that day: Whoever strikes the Jebusites, let him use the water shaft (<em>ṣinnôr</em>)... The water shaft (<em>ṣinnôr</em>) is connected by many archaeologists to Warren's Shaft — the vertical water system discovered by Charles Warren in 1867, providing subterranean access from inside the city to the Gihon Spring below. If soldiers could ascend through this system, the city's water-supply access became its point of vulnerability. 1 Chr 11:6 identifies Joab as the one who went up first through this route, explaining his appointment as commander. The reference to the blind and lame in v8 establishes a royal decree excluding them from the temple (though the tradition became complex in NT period).</p>",
    "9": "<p>David lived in the stronghold and called it the City of David. And David built the city all around from the Millo inward. The <em>Millōʾ</em> (from <em>mālēʾ</em>, to fill) refers to a fill structure — a terraced earthwork platform that extended the usable area of the narrow ridge. The Stepped Stone Structure discovered by Kenyon and further excavated by Eilat Mazar is the most likely candidate for the Millo, supporting a large building on the upper part of the City of David ridge. The phrase 'from the Millo inward' suggests the Millo marked the northern boundary of the original city expansion.</p>",
    "10": "<p>And David became greater and greater, for YHWH, the God of hosts, was with him (<em>wayyēleḵ dāwid hālôk wəgāḏôl waYHWH ʾelōhê ṣəḇāʾôṯ ʿimmô</em>). The formula — progressive growth + divine presence — is the standard narrative indicator that a biblical figure is operating under covenant blessing. YHWH <em>ṣəḇāʾôṯ</em> (God of hosts/armies) is the name associated with the ark (1 Sam 4:4) and with YHWH's military leadership — its use here reinforces the connection between David's military success and the ark's arrival in Jerusalem in ch6.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Hiram king of Tyre sent messengers to David with cedar trees, and carpenters and stonemasons, and they built David a house. Hiram I of Tyre (reigned c. 969-936 BCE by the higher chronology, or approximately contemporary with David) is the first Phoenician king to appear in the biblical narrative. The cedar trade from the Lebanese mountains was the primary luxury construction material in the ancient Levant — cedar was scarce in Canaan and exported by Phoenician maritime merchants. Phoenician craftsmen were specialists in ashlar stone construction; their appearance in David's palace marks the beginning of the Phoenician-Israelite architectural partnership that will culminate in Solomon's Temple (1 Kgs 5-7).</p>",
    "12": "<p>And David knew that YHWH had established him as king over Israel, and that he had exalted his kingdom for the sake of his people Israel. David's theological interpretation of his own success is the interpretive lens the narrative provides: the consolidation of the kingdom, the building of the palace, the Phoenician alliance — all are read as YHWH's action on behalf of his people, not David's personal achievement. The phrase <em>lǝmaʿan ʿammô yiśrāʾēl</em> (for the sake of his people Israel) places Israel as the ultimate beneficiary of the Davidic kingship.</p>",
    "13": "<p>And David took more concubines and wives from Jerusalem, after he came from Hebron, and more sons and daughters were born to David. The multiplication of wives in Jerusalem is the ANE practice of royal polygamy — kings used marriage alliances to seal political relationships. Deut 17:17 warned the future king not to multiply wives (<em>lō yarbeh-lô nāšîm</em>), a prohibition that David begins to violate here. The sons born in Jerusalem become the succession problem that drives the narrative from ch13 onward.</p>",
    "14": "<p>And these are the names of those who were born to him in Jerusalem: Shammua, Shobab, Nathan, Solomon, Ibhar, Elishua, Nepheg, Japhia, Elishama, Eliada, and Eliphelet. The Jerusalem-born sons are distinguished from the sons born at Hebron (3:2-5). Solomon appears fourth in this list — not the eldest son, which will become a succession problem requiring divine designation and human maneuvering (1 Kgs 1-2). The name Nathan appears here — a son of David named after the prophet, though this Nathan plays no role in the narrative.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Ibhar, Elishua, Nepheg, Japhia... (continuation of the list). The census of sons signals the expansion of the royal house. In ANE terms, a large royal family was evidence of divine blessing and political stability. The sons born to David in Jerusalem represent both the fulfillment of covenant blessing and the seeds of the succession crisis that will dominate 1 Kings.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Elishama, Eliada, and Eliphelet. The list ends with eleven names in this account (1 Chr 3:5-8 lists sixteen sons of the Jerusalem wives including four by Bathsheba). The difference may reflect different sources or different periods of compilation. The list's function is genealogical record-keeping that the later succession narratives will draw on.</p>",
    "17": "<p>When the Philistines heard that they had anointed David king over all Israel, all the Philistines went up to search for David. But David heard of it and went down to the stronghold. The Philistines had tolerated David as a vassal king over Judah (2:1-4) but the unification of all Israel under David represents a strategic threat they could not ignore. The 'stronghold' (<em>məṣûḏāh</em>) to which David descends may be the Cave of Adullam (1 Sam 22:1) or another Judean fortress. The Philistine campaign gives David the opportunity to consolidate his military position before his Jerusalem capital is fully secured.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Now the Philistines had come and spread out in the Valley of Rephaim (<em>ʿēmeq rəpāʾîm</em>). The Valley of Rephaim (modern Baqa/Baq'a, southwest of Jerusalem) was a fertile plain connecting the Shephelah to Jerusalem — a natural invasion corridor. The name connects to the Rephaim, the pre-Israelite inhabitants described elsewhere as giants. The valley's agricultural value (it was a grain-growing area, Isa 17:5) and its strategic position made it a recurring battleground.</p>",
    "19": "<p>And David inquired of YHWH, Shall I go up against the Philistines? Will you give them into my hand? And YHWH said to David, Go up, for I will certainly give the Philistines into your hand. The inquiry of YHWH before battle — presumably through the ephod and Urim/Thummim — is the practice the earlier narrative established (1 Sam 23:2,4; 30:8). David's consistent practice of seeking divine direction contrasts with Saul's unauthorized sacrifice (1 Sam 13) and resort to necromancy (1 Sam 28). The divine guarantee (<em>kî nāṯōn ʾettēn</em>, I will surely give) uses the infinitive-absolute emphasis.</p>",
    "20": "<p>And David came to Baal-perazim, and David defeated them there. And he said, YHWH has burst through my enemies before me like a bursting flood of waters. Therefore the name of that place is called Baal-perazim. The place-name Baal-perazim (lord/owner of breaking-through) is a commemorative name David coins on the spot — a practice common in the OT for theophanic or battle sites. The image of YHWH as a flood bursting through (*pāraṣ*) anticipates prophetic imagery of YHWH's irresistible advance (Isa 28:17, 30:28).</p>",
    "21": "<p>And they abandoned their idols there, and David and his men carried them off. The abandoned Philistine idols reflect the ANE practice of armies carrying their national deities into battle — the god's presence was thought to ensure victory. Their abandonment in retreat is the inversion of the ark narrative: where the Philistines captured Israel's ark (1 Sam 4-5), Israel now captures Philistia's idols. 1 Chr 14:12 adds that David commanded the idols to be burned — stricter compliance with Deut 7:5,25.</p>",
    "22": "<p>And the Philistines came up yet again and spread out in the Valley of Rephaim. A second invasion, in the same location — the Philistines have regrouped and returned. David inquires of YHWH again (v23) rather than assuming the previous oracle covers the new situation. The two-battle structure (vv17-21 and vv22-25) demonstrates that each campaign requires fresh divine guidance, not a standing permission to attack.</p>",
    "23": "<p>And David inquired of YHWH, and he said, You shall not go up; go around to their rear, and come against them opposite the balsam trees (<em>bəkāʾîm</em>). The different strategy for the second battle — flanking movement rather than frontal assault — indicates YHWH's tactical direction is specific to each situation. The <em>bəkāʾîm</em> (balsam trees, or possibly Aspen/mulberry) marked the terrain feature for the flanking position. The balsam tree has not been definitively identified archaeologically.</p>",
    "24": "<p>And when you hear the sound of marching (<em>qôl ṣaʿăḏāh</em>) in the tops of the balsam trees, then act, for then YHWH has gone out before you to strike the army of the Philistines. The signal is a natural phenomenon — the sound of wind moving through the treetops — interpreted as YHWH's advance. This is an example of YHWH using natural events as the timing signal for military action. The theophanic 'going out' of YHWH as a warrior before Israel is the imagery of the old Holy War tradition (Judg 4:14; 5:4-5).</p>",
    "25": "<p>And David did as YHWH commanded him, and struck down the Philistines from Geba to Gezer. The geographic spread — Geba (in Benjamin, northeast of Jerusalem) to Gezer (in the Shephelah, northwest) — indicates a decisive sweep that drove the Philistines back to their coastal territory. The two battles of the Valley of Rephaim effectively ended Philistine control of the highlands and secured Jerusalem as the Israelite capital free from immediate military threat.</p>"
  },
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>David again assembled all the chosen men of Israel, thirty thousand. The assembly of 30,000 for the ark procession matches the size of the force sent to bring the ark from Shiloh before the Aphek disaster (1 Sam 4:10: Israel fell, 30,000 foot soldiers). The parallel is deliberate — the ark's history from Shiloh to Kiriath-jearim (where it has sat for 20 years since 1 Sam 7:1-2) to Jerusalem is being framed as a national event of the same magnitude as the Aphek crisis.</p>",
    "2": "<p>David arose and went with all the people who were with him from Baale-judah to bring up from there the ark of God, which is called by the name of YHWH of hosts who sits enthroned on the cherubim. Baale-judah (= Kiriath-jearim, Josh 15:9, 'the heights of Judah') was where the ark had rested in the house of Abinadab since the Philistines returned it (1 Sam 7:1). The full name of the ark — 'called by the name of YHWH of hosts who sits enthroned on the cherubim' — is its most theologically loaded designation: the ark is both the footstool and the throne-base of YHWH's invisible presence, flanked by the cherubim figures. The 'sitting on the cherubim' motif appears in the iconography of ANE royal thrones, where winged composite creatures form the throne base.</p>",
    "3": "<p>And they set the ark of God on a new cart and brought it out of the house of Abinadab on the hill. Uzzah and Ahio, the sons of Abinadab, were guiding the new cart. The 'new cart' method was the procedure the Philistines had improvised when returning the ark (1 Sam 6:7-8) — it was not the prescribed Israelite method. Numbers 4:15 required the sons of Kohath (a Levitical family) to carry the ark on poles inserted through rings, on their shoulders. Numbers 7:9 explicitly states: 'to the sons of Kohath he gave none, because they were charged with the service of the holy things that had to be carried on the shoulder.' The Philistine cart-method, adopted without correction, sets up the crisis at the threshing floor.</p>",
    "4": "<p>And they brought it out of the house of Abinadab, which was on the hill, with the ark of God. Ahio went before the ark. The procession is festive and apparently well-organized — Uzzah walking beside/behind the cart to steady it if needed, Ahio walking ahead. The disaster that follows is not from lack of reverence or festivity but from an incorrect method of transport that required human hands to correct what poles would have prevented.</p>",
    "5": "<p>And David and all the house of Israel were celebrating before YHWH with all kinds of instruments made of fir wood, with lyres and harps and tambourines and castanets and cymbals. The musical celebration accompanies the ark procession — the same combination of instruments appears in the later psalms associated with the ark (Ps 150). The fir wood (<em>bərôšîm</em>, possibly cypress) instruments represent the finest available materials. The festive procession will be interrupted and then resumed in ch6 after a three-month pause.</p>",
    "6": "<p>And when they came to the threshing floor of Nacon (<em>gōren nāḵôn</em>), Uzzah put out his hand to the ark of God and took hold of it, for the oxen stumbled. The threshing floor (<em>gōren</em>) was a flat outdoor surface where grain was winnowed — the location suggests the cart traveled on a road near a threshing floor when the oxen stumbled. The stumble of the oxen is the occasion for the crisis, but the 1 Chr 15:13 retrospective identifies the root cause: 'because you did not carry it at the first, YHWH our God broke out against us, because we did not seek him according to the rule.'</p>",
    "7": "<p>And the anger of YHWH was kindled against Uzzah, and God struck him down there because of his error (<em>ʿal-haššal</em>), and he died there beside the ark of God. The word <em>šal</em> (error, irreverence, rashness) is rare and debated — it may mean 'rashness' or 'irreverence' rather than deliberate sin. Uzzah's death is not presented as punishment for malice but as the consequence of unauthorized contact with the ark. Numbers 4:15 explicitly warned: 'they must not touch any sacred thing, or they will die.' The transport method had already created a situation where human hands would be needed to prevent the ark from falling — the death of Uzzah is the outworking of the incorrect method, not merely of the contact itself.</p>",
    "8": "<p>And David was angry because YHWH had burst forth against Uzzah. And that place is called Perez-uzzah to this day. David's anger (<em>wayyiḥar lǝdāwid</em>) mirrors the language of YHWH's anger in v7 — a momentary shock response to what appeared to be an unjust death. Perez-uzzah (the breaking-out against Uzzah) is a commemorative place-name for the site of the crisis. David's anger is not condemned by the narrator but resolved in fear (v9) and eventually in proper inquiry about the correct procedure (1 Chr 15:2,13).</p>",
    "9": "<p>And David was afraid of YHWH that day, and he said, How can the ark of YHWH come to me? The fear (<em>wayyîrāʾ dāwid</em>) replaces anger as David reconsiders the significance of the event. His question — 'how can the ark come to me?' — reflects the recognition that approaching the holy presence of YHWH requires knowledge and procedure that he has not yet sought. The ark procession is halted; David diverts the ark to the nearby house of Obed-edom rather than continuing to Jerusalem.</p>",
    "10": "<p>So David was not willing to take the ark of YHWH into the city of David. But David took it aside to the house of Obed-edom the Gittite. Obed-edom the Gittite is identified in 1 Chr 26:4-8 as a Levite, from Gath-rimmon (a Levitical city in Manasseh, Josh 21:24-25) rather than the Philistine Gath — the 'Gittite' designation reflects his city of origin, not his ethnicity. As a Levite, Obed-edom's household was an appropriate temporary location for the ark, which explains why it could stay there safely while it had killed Uzzah on the cart.</p>",
    "11": "<p>And the ark of YHWH remained in the house of Obed-edom the Gittite three months, and YHWH blessed Obed-edom and all his household. The three-month blessing of Obed-edom's house becomes the news that reaches David (v12) and motivates him to resume the procession. The blessing is the positive counterpart to Uzzah's death: the ark brings death to those who approach it incorrectly and blessing to those who house it with reverence. 1 Chr 15-16 supplies the narrative of how David arranged for the Levites to carry the ark properly for the resumed procession.</p>",
    "12": "<p>And it was told King David, YHWH has blessed the household of Obed-edom and all that belongs to him, because of the ark of God. So David went and brought up the ark of God from the house of Obed-edom to the city of David with rejoicing. The three-month interval allowed David to discover the correct procedure (1 Chr 15:2: 'No one but the Levites may carry the ark of God, for YHWH chose them to carry the ark and to minister to him forever'). The resumed procession comes with proper Levitical transport and the sacrifices described in vv13-14.</p>",
    "13": "<p>And when those who bore the ark of YHWH had gone six steps, he sacrificed an ox and a fattened animal. The sacrifice after six steps is the ritual acknowledgment that the resumed procession is operating under YHWH's blessing — the progression proceeds six steps (representing the six days of creation or simply a unit of distance) and then stops for sacrifice. The Levitical bearers are implied by the verb 'those who bore' — the cart has been replaced by human carriers on shoulders as required by the Torah.</p>",
    "14": "<p>And David danced before YHWH with all his might. And David was wearing a linen ephod (<em>ʾēpôḏ bāḏ</em>). The linen ephod was a priestly garment (1 Sam 2:18: Samuel wore one as a boy; 1 Sam 22:18: the priests of Nob wore them). David's wearing it suggests he assumed a quasi-priestly role in the procession — the Davidic king exercising a priestly function at the transfer of the ark. The later tradition develops David's priestly-royal role (Ps 110:4: 'You are a priest forever after the order of Melchizedek'). David's dancing before YHWH with all his might is the Hebrew expression of complete, uninhibited worship: <em>məkarker bəkol-ʿōz</em> (leaping/whirling with all his strength).</p>",
    "15": "<p>So David and all the house of Israel brought up the ark of YHWH with shouting and with the sound of the horn (<em>bəqôl šôpār</em>). The shofar (<em>šôpār</em>) was used at theophanic events (Exod 19:16,19: Sinai), battle signals (Num 10:9), and royal coronations (2 Sam 15:10; 1 Kgs 1:34). Its use here marks the ark's arrival in Jerusalem as a quasi-coronation event — YHWH the king returning to his city in triumph.</p>",
    "16": "<p>As the ark of YHWH came into the city of David, Michal the daughter of Saul looked out of the window and saw King David leaping and dancing before YHWH, and she despised him in her heart. Michal's watching from the window (<em>wattaśqēp... bəʿaḏ haḥallôn</em>) is an ironic echo of the 'watching from the window' motif in Israelite narrative: Sisera's mother watches from the window waiting for her son's return (Judg 5:28); Jezebel looks from a window at Jehu's approach (2 Kgs 9:30). In each case, the woman at the window represents a power about to be displaced. Michal's contempt for David's worship will result in her permanent childlessness — the house of Saul ends with her.</p>",
    "17": "<p>And they brought in the ark of YHWH and set it in its place, inside the tent that David had pitched for it. And David offered burnt offerings and peace offerings before YHWH. The temporary tent shelter (as opposed to a permanent temple) echoes the tabernacle tradition — YHWH has dwelt in a tent throughout the wilderness period and the judges period. David pitches a new tent for the ark in Jerusalem, the forerunner of the Temple. His personal offering of burnt offerings and peace offerings — normally a priestly function — reflects the Davidic priestly-royal role at the ark.</p>",
    "18": "<p>And when David had finished offering the burnt offerings and the peace offerings, he blessed the people in the name of YHWH of hosts. The royal blessing of the people after the sacrifice is another quasi-priestly act — the Aaronic blessing (Num 6:24-26) was the priests' function. David's blessing 'in the name of YHWH of hosts' connects to the ark's full title (v2) and to the military theology of the ark's presence.</p>",
    "19": "<p>And he distributed among all the people, the whole multitude of Israel, both men and women, to each a cake of bread, a portion of meat, and a cake of raisins. And all the people departed, each to his house. The distribution of food to all Israel — regardless of gender or social status — is a statement of covenant solidarity. The food gifts (bread cake, meat portion, raisin cake) are the same kinds of items given at feasts and sacred meals. The equal distribution signals that the ark's arrival is a benefit for all Israel, not just the cultic specialists.</p>",
    "20": "<p>David returned to bless his household. And Michal the daughter of Saul came out to meet David and said, How the king of Israel honored himself today, uncovering himself today before the eyes of his servants' female servants, as one of the vulgar fellows shamelessly uncovers himself! Michal's accusation — that David exposed himself inappropriately before the servant girls — is likely an exaggeration born of contempt rather than a literal report. The linen ephod was a garment that covered more than the usual soldier's battle gear but less than royal robes; dancing in it might have exposed him in ways a king's dignity was not supposed to permit. Michal's frame of reference is Saulide royal dignity; David's is uninhibited devotion to YHWH.</p>",
    "21": "<p>And David said to Michal, It was before YHWH, who chose me above your father and above all his house, to appoint me as prince over Israel, the people of YHWH — and I will celebrate before YHWH. David's response explicitly invokes the election theology: YHWH chose David over Saul. The contrast between Michal's framework (royal dignity) and David's (YHWH's choice) reveals the theological divide between the Saulide understanding of kingship (honor and dignity before the people) and the Davidic understanding (the king as YHWH's servant whose first obligation is worship, not self-presentation).</p>",
    "22": "<p>I will become even more undignified than this, and I will be abased in my own eyes. But by the female servants of whom you have spoken, by them I shall be held in honor. David's willingness to be further undignified before YHWH — and his prediction that the very women Michal mocked him for performing before will honor him — is the inversion of the honor calculus Michal operates with. The pattern is the same as the Magnificat's reversal: the proud are brought low and the humble are exalted.</p>",
    "23": "<p>And Michal the daughter of Saul had no child to the day of her death. The closing note of Michal's childlessness is the narrative consequence of her contempt for David's worship. The end of Michal's line is the end of Saul's direct line through David's house — the dynastic future belongs entirely to David's sons by other wives. The phrase 'daughter of Saul' (rather than 'wife of David') throughout this episode keeps her Saulide identity in the foreground.</p>"
  },
  "7": {
    "2": "<p>The king said to Nathan the prophet: See now, I dwell in a house of cedar, but the ark of God dwells in a tent. David's contrast between his own cedar palace (built with Hiram's timber, 5:11) and the ark's tent housing is the motivation for his temple-building desire. In ANE royal ideology, a king who did not build or restore the chief temple of the national god was failing in a primary royal obligation — the Mesopotamian kings and Egyptian pharaohs built temples as their primary piety-demonstrations. David's impulse fits this cultural context; YHWH's response subverts it entirely.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Nathan said to the king: Go, do all that is in your heart, for YHWH is with you. Nathan's initial response — 'do all that is in your heart' — is the prophet speaking from his own wisdom rather than from a divine oracle. His response in v3 is a human-wisdom judgment: if the king is godly and YHWH is with him, his desire to honor YHWH with a temple must be good. The correction comes that night (v4): prophetic guidance sometimes proceeds by initial human assessment followed by divine correction.</p>",
    "4": "<p>But that same night the word of YHWH came to Nathan. The night-oracle is a common prophetic vehicle (Gen 20:3,6; 1 Sam 3:4-9; 1 Kgs 3:5). The contrast between Nathan's daytime human wisdom response and the night divine word highlights the distinction between the prophet's own assessment and YHWH's revelation. The correction is immediate — 'that same night' — not delayed.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Go and tell my servant David: Thus says YHWH: Would you build me a house to dwell in? YHWH's question is rhetorical — it challenges the premise of David's proposal. The question 'would you build me a house?' (<em>haʾattāh tibneh-lî bayit</em>) uses the emphatic <em>haʾattāh</em> — would you, of all people, build me a house? The implication is not that the temple is wrong in principle but that David is not the one to build it (1 Chr 22:8: because you are a man of war and have shed blood).</p>",
    "6": "<p>I have not lived in a house since the day I brought up the people of Israel from Egypt to this day, but I have been moving about in a tent for my dwelling. The divine self-disclosure of vv6-7 is YHWH's review of his own dwelling history: tent/tabernacle movement throughout the wilderness and conquest periods. YHWH had not requested a permanent house; he had been content to move with his people. The question 'did I speak a word saying, why have you not built me a house of cedar?' (v7) is rhetorical: no such demand had been made.</p>",
    "7": "<p>In all places where I have moved with all the people of Israel, did I speak a word with any of the judges of Israel, whom I commanded to shepherd my people Israel, saying, Why have you not built me a house of cedar? The judges are invoked as the category of leaders who preceded the monarchy — none of them had been commanded to build a temple. The implication is that the temple is David's human initiative, not a divine requirement — and YHWH is about to redirect it by making David the subject of building rather than its executor.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Now therefore thus you shall say to my servant David: Thus says YHWH of hosts, I took you from the pasture, from following the sheep, that you should be prince over my people Israel. YHWH's recitation of David's elevation — from shepherd to prince — is the covenant history of grace that undergirds the covenant promise about to be made. The shepherd-to-king trajectory (<em>min-hannāweh... mēʾaḥar haṣṣōʾn</em>, from the pasture, from behind the flock) is the reversal of status that YHWH himself executed.</p>",
    "9": "<p>And I have been with you wherever you went and have cut off all your enemies from before you. And I will make for you a great name, like the name of the great ones of the earth. YHWH's past action — 'I have been with you, I have cut off your enemies' — establishes the basis for the future covenant. The promise of a great name (<em>šēm gāḏôl</em>) echoes the Tower of Babel builders' goal ('let us make a name for ourselves', Gen 11:4) but now comes as divine gift rather than human achievement.</p>",
    "10": "<p>And I will appoint a place for my people Israel and will plant them, so that they may dwell in their own place and be disturbed no more. And violent men shall afflict them no more, as formerly. The promise of a secure homeland for Israel is embedded within the Davidic covenant — it is not just a covenant about David's dynasty but about Israel's dwelling security. The verb <em>nāṭaʿ</em> (to plant) is the agricultural metaphor for permanent settlement: YHWH will plant Israel like a tree that is not uprooted.</p>",
    "11": "<p>From the time that I appointed judges over my people Israel. And I will give you rest from all your enemies. Moreover, YHWH declares to you that YHWH will make you a house. The great reversal of v11b: David wanted to build YHWH a house (<em>bayit</em>); YHWH declares that he will build David a house (<em>bayit</em>). The word <em>bayit</em> carries three meanings simultaneously: a physical building (the temple), a dynasty (a royal household), and a son (who will build both). This wordplay is the structural center of the whole oracle.</p>",
    "12": "<p>When your days are fulfilled and you lie down with your fathers, I will raise up your offspring after you, who shall come from your body, and I will establish his kingdom. The Davidic covenant's core promise: a successor who comes from David's body (<em>ʾăšer yēṣēʾ mimmeʿeḵā</em>, who goes forth from your inward parts) whose kingdom YHWH will establish. The near fulfillment is Solomon (1 Kgs 1-11); the far fulfillment, anticipated in the Psalms and prophets, is the eternal heir whose kingdom has no end.</p>",
    "13": "<p>He shall build a house for my name, and I will establish the throne of his kingdom forever (<em>ʿad-ʿôlām</em>). The promise is twofold: the son builds the temple (near fulfillment: Solomon, 1 Kgs 6-8), and YHWH establishes his throne forever (the eschatological element that points beyond Solomon). The phrase <em>ʿad-ʿôlām</em> (forever, to the age) is the standard temporal marker for permanence in covenant promises — it cannot be satisfied by any mortal king and generates the messianic expectation.</p>",
    "14": "<p>I will be to him a father, and he shall be to me a son. When he commits iniquity, I will discipline him with the rod of men, with the stripes of the sons of men. The father-son language is the covenant's most intimate dimension. The discipline provision (<em>bəšēbeṭ ʾănāšîm ûbənigʿê ḇənê ʾāḏām</em>, with the rod of men and the blows of human beings) distinguishes the Davidic covenant from the Mosaic: human instruments of discipline rather than covenant termination. The provision is applied to Solomon's failures (1 Kgs 11) and to the exile of the later Davidic kings — but YHWH's covenant-love (<em>ḥeseḏ</em>) will not be removed.</p>",
    "15": "<p>But my steadfast love will not depart from him (<em>waḥasdi lō-yāsûr mimmennû</em>), as I took it from Saul, whom I put away from before you. The Saul contrast is the theological heart of the discipline provision: Saul's rejection was permanent (<em>waʾāsîr</em>, I turned aside); David's dynasty will be disciplined but not abandoned. The <em>ḥeseḏ</em> (covenant-loyalty, steadfast love) that is withheld from Saul's house is the permanent possession of David's. This is the OT's clearest articulation of unconditional covenant love within a relationship that still includes discipline.</p>",
    "16": "<p>And your house and your kingdom shall be made sure forever before me. Your throne shall be established forever (<em>ʿad-ʿôlām</em>). The oracle closes with the double <em>ʿad-ʿôlām</em> promise — house, kingdom, throne — all established permanently. The repetition ensures that no element of the Davidic grant is temporary. Ps 89 will later wrestle with the apparent contradiction between this promise and the exile of the Davidic line, and Ps 110 will articulate the eschatological dimension of the eternal throne.</p>",
    "17": "<p>In accordance with all these words and in accordance with all this vision, Nathan spoke to David. The oracle closes with the double authenticating formula: words (<em>dəḇārîm</em>) and vision (<em>ḥāzôn</em>). The vision may be the night-oracle of v4; the words are the covenant promise. Nathan delivers both — the account confirms that the prophet's function is to transmit divine word with full fidelity, not to interpret or modify it.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Then King David went in and sat before YHWH and said: Who am I, O Lord YHWH, and what is my house, that you have brought me thus far? David's prayer begins with the question of unworthiness: <em>mî ʾănî</em> (who am I?) is the classic response to an unexpected divine call or promise (Moses: Exod 3:11; Gideon: Judg 6:15; Saul: 1 Sam 9:21). Sitting before YHWH — presumably in the tent that housed the ark — is the posture of attending, waiting, receiving, as distinguished from the standing posture of prayer in distress.</p>",
    "19": "<p>And yet this was a small thing in your eyes, O Lord YHWH. You have spoken also of your servant's house for a great while to come (<em>wəzōʾt ûmērāḥôq</em>). And this is instruction for mankind, O Lord YHWH. The phrase <em>wəzōʾt tôraṯ hāʾāḏām</em> ('this is the charter/instruction for humanity') is debated — some translate 'this is the law/custom for man' or 'this is the destiny of mankind.' David may be recognizing that the Davidic covenant has implications beyond Israel — a point the prophets will develop when they speak of all nations coming to the Davidic king (Isa 9:6-7; 11:10; Ps 72:8-11).</p>",
    "20": "<p>And what more can David say to you? For you know your servant, O Lord YHWH! David's rhetorical question — 'what more can I say?' — is an acknowledgment that language is insufficient before divine grace. The affirmation 'you know your servant' (<em>wəʾattāh yādaʿtā ʾeṯ-ʿaḇdəḵā</em>) is the covenantal intimacy of YHWH's knowledge: the divine knowledge that sees David completely and still makes the covenant.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Because of your promise, and according to your own heart, you have brought about all this greatness, to make your servant know it. The covenant promise derives from YHWH's own heart (<em>ûḇilbāḇəḵā ʿāśîṯā</em>, according to your own heart you have done): it is not an obligation but a free act of divine love and commitment. David marvels that YHWH has made him know the greatness of the promise — the gift includes the revelation of the gift's significance.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Therefore you are great, O YHWH God. For there is none like you, and there is no God besides you, according to all that we have heard with our ears. The doxology — <em>ʾên kāmôḵā wəʾên ʾelōhîm zûlāṯeḵā</em> (there is none like you, and there is no God apart from you) — is the OT's incomparability formula. It appears in Exod 15:11 (the Song of Moses), in Hannah's prayer (1 Sam 2:2), and here. The Davidic covenant's ground is the incomparable uniqueness of YHWH.</p>",
    "23": "<p>And who is like your people Israel, the one nation on earth whom God went to redeem to be his people, making himself a name and doing for them great and awesome things by driving out before your people, whom you redeemed for yourself from Egypt, a nation and its gods? Israel's uniqueness (<em>mî kəʿammǝḵā yiśrāʾēl gôy ʾeḥāḏ bāʾāreṣ</em>, who is like your people, one nation on the earth?) mirrors the divine incomparability formula: YHWH is unique among gods; Israel is unique among nations. The election of Israel and the incomparability of YHWH are correlative claims — both rest on the same divine freedom and grace.</p>",
    "24": "<p>And you established for yourself your people Israel to be your people forever. And you, O YHWH, became their God. The mutual establishment formula — 'you established Israel as your people... and you became their God' — is the covenant formula in its most concise form. This bidirectional covenant relationship (YHWH's people / Israel's God) is the theological core of the Sinai covenant now extended and deepened by the Davidic covenant.</p>",
    "25": "<p>And now, O YHWH God, confirm forever the word that you have spoken concerning your servant and concerning his house, and do as you have spoken. David's intercession inverts the typical petition: he is not asking for something new but asking YHWH to do what he has already promised. The confidence of covenantal prayer is precisely this — appealing to YHWH's own word as the ground of the request. <em>qūm</em> (arise/stand/confirm) + <em>kaʾăšer dibbartā</em> (as you have spoken): confirm what you said.</p>",
    "26": "<p>And your name will be magnified forever, saying, YHWH of hosts is God over Israel, and the house of your servant David will be established before you. The magnification of YHWH's name (<em>yigdal šimḵā lǝʿôlām</em>) is the ultimate goal of the Davidic covenant: not the greatness of the Davidic dynasty for its own sake but the magnification of YHWH's name through it. The doxological purpose of the covenant is explicit.</p>",
    "27": "<p>For you, O YHWH of hosts, the God of Israel, have made this revelation to your servant, saying, I will build you a house. Therefore your servant has found courage to pray this prayer to you. David's prayer rests entirely on YHWH's revelation — <em>gāliṯā ʾet-ʾōzen ʾaḇdəḵā</em> (you have uncovered the ear of your servant), the idiom for special disclosure. The courage to pray (<em>māṣāʾ ʾaḇdəḵā ʾeṯ-libbo lhitpallel</em>, your servant has found his heart to pray) comes from the promise, not from David's own confidence or worthiness.</p>",
    "28": "<p>And now, O Lord YHWH, you are God, and your words are true (<em>wadeḇāreḵā yihyû ʾemeṯ</em>), and you have promised this good thing to your servant. The truth and reliability of YHWH's word (<em>ʾemeṯ</em>, truth/faithfulness) is the epistemological ground for David's prayer. The covenant promise is reliable because YHWH's word is reliable — the two propositions are inseparable in OT theology.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Now therefore may it please you to bless the house of your servant, so that it may continue forever before you. For you, O Lord YHWH, have spoken, and with your blessing shall the house of your servant be blessed forever. The prayer ends with the final petition and its doxological grounding: 'you have spoken' — the Davidic covenant's ground is always the divine word. The blessing David asks for his house is grounded not in his own merit but in YHWH's prior speech. The repetition of <em>lǝʿôlām</em> (forever) at the end of the prayer mirrors the threefold <em>ʿad-ʿôlām</em> of the oracle — David's prayer takes up the language of the promise and returns it to YHWH as intercession.</p>"
  }
}

